'''Yukawa''' (湯川) is a [[river]] in [[Nagano Prefecture]], flowing through [[Karuizawa Town]], [[Miyota Town]], and [[Saku City]]. It is a [[first-class river]] in the [[:en:Shinano River|Shinano River]] system. During the [[Edo Period]], it was also known as Uogawa, Ōgawa, and Hanazugawa.<ref>''Nakasendō Volume 7'', Tokyo Bijutsu, September 30, 1979, p. 10.</ref>
== Geography ==
Yukawa originates near the northern part of [[Asama Volcano]] in [[Karuizawa Town]], Nagano Prefecture. It flows through notable locations like {{ill|Shiraito Falls (Nagano)|ja|白糸の滝 (長野県)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shiraito Falls (Nagano)|qq=}}, {{ill|Sengataki Falls (Karuizawa)|ja|千ヶ滝 (軽井沢町)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sengataki Falls (Karuizawa)|qq=}}, and [[Usui Pass]], joining the Chikuma River (the local name for the Shinano River) at Naruse in Saku City. In Miyota Town, the Yukawa Valley houses the [[Yukawa Dam]], a prefectural [[flood control dam]] managed by Nagano Prefecture.
== Administrative Designation ==
The river has the following designations:<ref>Cabinet Order No. 43, March 24, 1965: "Ordinance Specifying River Systems and First-Class Rivers Under Article 4, Paragraph 1 of the River Act."</ref> * River designation: First-class river (designated in [[:en:1965|1965]]) * Endpoints: ** Upstream: Nagakura, Karuizawa Town, Nagano Prefecture, at the Shishiiwa land plot ** Downstream: Confluence with the Shinano River * Water system designation: [[First-class water system]], Shinano River system (designated in 1965)
